>[Thoughts]
>I thought that if I could find two linearly independent solutions to 
>the homogeneous case then I could used these two solutions and their 
>Wronskian to find the solution that solved the initial value problem.
>
>I tried a few ideas out and basically found by observation that the 
>d.e. 
>
>     y'' + Cy = 0
>
>can be solved with
>
>     C = 1 and y_1 = cos(x) 
>or
>
>     C = 1 and y_1 = sin(x)
>
>I know of a theorem that gives the formula
>
>
>   Y(x) = y2 * int[y1/W]dt - y1 * int[y2/W]dt
>
>Perhaps I can use this formalu to get the solution?
